'''Jam City, Inc.''' (formerly '''MindJolt''' and '''Social Gaming Network''') is an American [[video game developer]] based in [[Culver City, California]]. The company was founded in 2010 by [[Chris DeWolfe]], [[Colin Digiaro]], [[Aber Whitcomb]], and [[Josh Yguado]]. Jam City has nine studios located in the United States, Canada, South America, and Europe.<ref>{{cite news |title=Former Myspace Mogul Chris DeWolfe Reflects on Mobile Gaming's Future |last=Shanley |first=Patrick |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/myspace-mogul-chris-dewolfe-reflects-mobile-gamings-future-1278540 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=February 13, 2020 |access-date=March 10, 2021 |archive-date=September 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200921132743/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/myspace-mogul-chris-dewolfe-reflects-mobile-gamings-future-1278540 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Chapple |first=Craig |url=https://www.pocketgamer.biz/news/70410/jam-city-acquires-berlin-studio-231-play/ |title=Jam City acquires Berlin studio 231 Play |work=[[Pocket Gamer]] |date=April 5, 2019 |access-date=February 18, 2021 |archive-date=December 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201201173926/https://www.pocketgamer.biz/news/70410/jam-city-acquires-berlin-studio-231-play/ |url-status=live }}</ref> As of 2021, it employs 825 people.<ref name="GamesBeatSPAC">{{cite news |title=Harry Potter: Hogwarts Mystery publisher Jam City will launch SPAC at $1.2B value, buy Ludia for $175M |last=Takahashi |first=Dean |url=https://venturebeat.com/2021/05/20/harry-potter-game-maker-jam-city-will-launch-spac-at-1-2b-value-and-buy-ludia-for-175m/ |work=[[GamesBeat]] |date=May 20, 2021 |access-date=May 21, 2021 |archive-date=May 20, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210520200530/https://venturebeat.com/2021/05/20/harry-potter-game-maker-jam-city-will-launch-spac-at-1-2b-value-and-buy-ludia-for-175m/ |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Netmarble]] is the largest shareholder in Jam City. As of 2021, Jam City's games have 31&nbsp;million [[monthly active users]] and 1.3&nbsp;[[1,000,000,000|billion]] total downloads.

== History ==
Jam City was founded by the [[Myspace]] co-founders [[Chris DeWolfe]], [[Colin Digiaro]] and [[Aber Whitcomb]], and former [[20th Century Fox]] executive Josh Yguado.<ref name="TechCrunch March2010">{{cite web |url=https://techcrunch.com/2010/03/03/chris-dewolfe-mindjolt-austin-ventures/ |title=Chris DeWolfe Makes His Move – Raises Big Round, Acquires Gaming Platform MindJolt |date=March 3, 2010 |last=Arrington |first=Michael |website=[[TechCrunch]] |access-date=January 23, 2017 |archive-date=September 23, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923224436/https://techcrunch.com/2010/03/03/chris-dewolfe-mindjolt-austin-ventures/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |access-date=June 1, 2018 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/talkingtech/2017/03/22/jam-city-seeks-another-hit-more-family-guy-plans-ipo/99431382 |title=Jam City seeks another hit with more Family Guy, plans for IPO |work=USA Today |location=Tysons Corner, VA |date=March 22, 2017 |author=Graham, Jefferson |archive-date=June 12, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612170028/https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/talkingtech/2017/03/22/jam-city-seeks-another-hit-more-family-guy-plans-ipo/99431382/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |access-date=June 1, 2018 |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kathleenchaykowski/2017/06/12/former-myspace-ceo-makes-a-comeback-as-a-mobile-gaming-hitmaker |title=Former MySpace CEO Makes A Comeback As A Mobile Gaming Hitmaker |work=Forbes |location=New York, NY |date=June 12, 2017 |author=Chaykowski, Kathleen |archive-date=June 12, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612144621/https://www.forbes.com/sites/kathleenchaykowski/2017/06/12/former-myspace-ceo-makes-a-comeback-as-a-mobile-gaming-hitmaker |url-status=live}}</ref> The company launched in 2010 when the co-founders raised {{US$|28&nbsp;million|link=yes}} from [[Austin Ventures]] for their business, then called Platform G.<ref name="TechCrunch March2010" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Spangler |first=Todd |url=https://variety.com/2015/digital/news/sgn-netmarble-funding-mobile-games-1201546770/ |title=Mobile-Game Studio SGN Lands $130 Million from Korea's Netmarble |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=July 23, 2015 |access-date=February 17, 2021 |archive-date=November 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201108153238/https://variety.com/2015/digital/news/sgn-netmarble-funding-mobile-games-1201546770/ |url-status=live}}</ref> Platform G acquired MindJolt, a [[Social-network game|social gaming]] platform founded by Richard Fields, in March 2010 and took its name.<ref name="TechCrunch March2010" /> Fields remained with the company to lead strategy.<ref name="TechCrunch March2010" /> The new MindJolt acquired Social Gaming Network (or SGN) and Hallpass Media in April 2011, which added [[mobile game]]s to the company's portfolio.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2011/04/18/a-myspace-founder-is-building-again-with-online-games/ |title=A Myspace Founder Builds Again, Buying Game Companies |date=April 18, 2011 |last=Rusli |first=Evelyn M. |website=New York Times Dealbook |access-date=January 23, 2017 |archive-date=March 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319085028/https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2011/04/18/a-myspace-founder-is-building-again-with-online-games/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Forbes June2013" /> MindJolt renamed as SGN in March 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://techcrunch.com/2012/03/02/mindjolt-becomes-social-gaming-network/ |title=MySpace Co-Founder Chris DeWolfe Explains SGN's New Name, Multi-Platform Plans |date=March 2, 2012 |last=Ha |first=Anthony |website=TechCrunch |access-date=January 23, 2017 |archive-date=September 23, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923080602/https://techcrunch.com/2012/03/02/mindjolt-becomes-social-gaming-network/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Variety September2016">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2016/digital/news/sgn-jam-city-peanuts-mobile-game-1201867364/ |title=SGN Changes Name to Jam City, Acquires Rights to Make 'Peanuts' Mobile Game |date=September 22, 2016 |last=Spangler |first=Todd |website=Variety |publisher=Variety Media, LLC |access-date=January 10, 2017 |archive-date=February 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170215230955/http://variety.com/2016/digital/news/sgn-jam-city-peanuts-mobile-game-1201867364/ |url-status=live}}</ref> In June 2013, SGN acquired Mob Science, a developer of social games known for ''Legends: Rise of a Hero''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adweek.com/socialtimes/social-gaming-network-mob-science/423171 |title=Social Gaming Network's Acquisition Of Mob Science Continues Trend Away From Facebook-Only Social Games |date=June 17, 2013 |last=M |first=Will |website=[[AdWeek]]: Social Times |access-date=January 23, 2017 |archive-date=April 2, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402062655/http://www.adweek.com/socialtimes/social-gaming-network-mob-science/423171 |url-status=live}}</ref> The company launched the game ''Panda Pop'' in 2013, which would later become one of the highest-grossing mobile games.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.pocketgamer.biz/news/66479/panda-pop-100-million-downloads/ |title=Jam City's Panda Pop clears 100 million downloads in under four years |date=August 25, 2017 |last=Cowley |first=Ric |work=[[Pocket Gamer]] |access-date=February 23, 2021 |archive-date=January 23, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210123022117/https://www.pocketgamer.biz/news/66479/panda-pop-100-million-downloads/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Panda Pop passes 100 million users as Jam City readies for an IPO |last=Shieber |first=Jonathan |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/08/24/panda-pop-readies-jam-city-closeup/ |work=[[TechCrunch]] |date=August 24, 2017 |access-date=March 10, 2021 |archive-date=November 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201127151838/https://techcrunch.com/2017/08/24/panda-pop-readies-jam-city-closeup/ |url-status=live}}</ref> The match-3 [[puzzle game]] ''Cookie Jam'' launched in 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2014/03/24/cookie-jam-app-review/6824875/ |title='Cookie Jam': A tasty puzzle game with new twists |date=March 24, 2014 |last=Saltzman |first=Marc |work=[[USA Today]] |access-date=February 23, 2021 |archive-date=February 22, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222015015/https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2014/03/24/cookie-jam-app-review/6824875/ |url-status=live}}</ref> ''Cookie Jam'' was named [[Facebook]]'s game of the year with more than 100&nbsp;million downloads and 5&nbsp;million active players at the time.<ref name="VBCookieJam">{{cite news |access-date=June 27, 2018 |url=https://venturebeat.com/2017/05/24/jam-citys-cookie-jam-hits-100-million-downloads-as-cookie-jam-blast-debuts |title=Jam City's Cookie Jam hits 100 million downloads as Cookie Jam Blast debuts |work=VentureBeat |location=San Francisco, CA |date=May 24, 2017 |author=Takahashi, Dean |archive-date=June 12, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612205332/https://venturebeat.com/2017/05/24/jam-citys-cookie-jam-hits-100-million-downloads-as-cookie-jam-blast-debuts/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/business/technology/la-fi-tn-cookie-jam-netease-20141216-story.html |title=Mobile game 'Cookie Jam' latest hit being exported to China |date=December 16, 2014 |last=Dave |first=Paresh |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |access-date=February 23, 2021 |archive-date=June 12, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612144558/http://www.latimes.com/business/technology/la-fi-tn-cookie-jam-netease-20141216-story.html |url-status=live}}</ref> ''Cookie Jam'' was also among the 20 highest-grossing mobile games for [[Google Play]] and the [[App Store (iOS/iPadOS)|App Store]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Maker of 'Cookie Jam' Lands $130 Million Investment From Korea's Top Gaming Giant |last=Zipkin |first=Nina |url=https://www.entrepreneur.com/article/248739 |work=[[Entrepreneur (magazine)|Entrepreneur]] |date=July 23, 2015 |access-date=March 10, 2021 |archive-date=February 24, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210224005045/https://www.entrepreneur.com/article/248739 |url-status=live}}</ref>

In the wake of ''Cookie Jam''{{'}}s success, the South Korean mobile game company [[Netmarble]] invested {{US$|130&nbsp;million|long=no}} in SGN in July 2015, becoming SGN's largest shareholder; this was one of the largest investments in mobile gaming since 2013.<ref>{{cite news |title=Netmarble Takes Stake in SGN, Extending Asia's Reach Into U.S. Mobile Games |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/23/technology/netmarble-takes-stake-in-sgn-extending-asias-reach-into-us-mobile-games.html?_r=1 |date=July 23, 2015 |last=Zimmerman |first=Eilene |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=January 13, 2017 |archive-date=January 16, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180116135655/https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/23/technology/netmarble-takes-stake-in-sgn-extending-asias-reach-into-us-mobile-games.html?_r=1 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fastcompany.com/3048962/tech-forecast/why-this-mobile-game-company-raised-130-million |title=Why This Mobile Game Company Raised $130 Million |date=July 23, 2015 |last=Ungerleider |first=Neal |website=[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]] |publisher=Mansueto Ventures, LLC |access-date=January 13, 2017 |archive-date=January 31, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170131023931/https://www.fastcompany.com/3048962/tech-forecast/why-this-mobile-game-company-raised-130-million |url-status=live}}</ref> By the time of Netmarble's investment, SGN games had been downloaded 500&nbsp;million times.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mobile-Game Studio SGN Lands $130 Million from Korea's Netmarble |last=Spangler |first=Todd |url=https://variety.com/2015/digital/asia/sgn-netmarble-funding-mobile-games-1201546770/ |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=July 23, 2015 |access-date=March 10, 2021 |archive-date=September 20, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920190428/https://variety.com/2015/digital/asia/sgn-netmarble-funding-mobile-games-1201546770/ |url-status=live}}</ref> Following Netmarble's investment, SGN bought the developers Fat Rascal Games and Kiwi Inc. in late 2015, followed by [[TinyCo]] in July 2016. The latter acquisition raised SGN's staff count from 125 to 400.<ref>{{cite web |last=Ellingson |first=Annlee |date=July 6, 2016 |title=SGN buys startup behind Marvel, 'Family Guy' mobile games |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/losangeles/news/2016/07/06/sgn-buys-startup-behind-marvel-family-guy-mobile.html |access-date=January 10, 2017 |website=Biz Journals |publisher=American City Business Journals |archive-date=February 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170215121228/http://www.bizjournals.com/losangeles/news/2016/07/06/sgn-buys-startup-behind-marvel-family-guy-mobile.html |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2016/digital/news/sgn-tinyco-marvel-avengers-academy-1201809201/ |title=SGN Buys TinyCo, Maker of 'Marvel Avengers Academy' Mobile Game |date=July 6, 2016 |last=Spangler |first=Todd |website=Variety |publisher=Variety Media, LLC |access-date=January 10, 2017 |archive-date=February 26, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170226215332/http://variety.com/2016/digital/news/sgn-tinyco-marvel-avengers-academy-1201809201/ |url-status=live}}</ref> Mobile entertainment games that TinyCo had created include ''Family Guy: The Quest for Stuff'' and ''Marvel Avengers Academy''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.alistdaily.com/strategy/sgn-talks-acquiring-tinyco-future-mobile-games-industry/ |title=SGN Talks About Acquiring TinyCo, Future Of Mobile Games Industry |date=July 7, 2016 |last=Peterson |first=Steve |website=A List Daily |publisher=Ayzenberg |access-date=January 10, 2017 |archive-date=February 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170215195637/http://www.alistdaily.com/strategy/sgn-talks-acquiring-tinyco-future-mobile-games-industry/ |url-status=live}}</ref> SGN rebranded as Jam City in September 2016,<ref name="Variety September2016" /> the same year ''Genies & Gems'', a match-3 puzzle game, was launched.<ref name="VBFreakin">{{cite news |url=https://venturebeat.com/2017/04/25/how-jam-city-ceo-chris-dewolfe-sees-the-freakin-mobile-game-world/ |title=How Jam City CEO Chris DeWolfe sees the freakin' mobile game world |date=April 25, 2017 |work=[[VentureBeat]] |access-date=February 23, 2021 |archive-date=September 22, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200922084459/https://venturebeat.com/2017/04/25/how-jam-city-ceo-chris-dewolfe-sees-the-freakin-mobile-game-world/ |url-status=live}}</ref>

On April 25, 2018, Jam City released ''[[Harry Potter: Hogwarts Mystery]]'', a mobile game based on [[J. K. Rowling]]'s [[Wizarding World]] franchise.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://venturebeat.com/2018/04/26/harry-potter-hogwarts-mystery-tops-apple-app-store-charts-a-day-after-launch/ |title=Harry Potter: Hogwarts Mystery tops Apple App Store charts a day after launch |last=Chan |first=Stephanie |work=[[VentureBeat]] |date=April 26, 2018 |access-date=February 23, 2021 |archive-date=November 9, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201109043244/https://venturebeat.com/2018/04/26/harry-potter-hogwarts-mystery-tops-apple-app-store-charts-a-day-after-launch/ |url-status=live}}</ref> Within its first day, the game was ranked first on the App Store's free-to-play category and reached tenth place on the list of top-grossing games across categories.<ref>{{cite news |title=Harry Potter: Hogwarts Mystery tops Apple App Store charts a day after launch |last=Chan |first=Stephanie |url=https://venturebeat.com/2018/04/26/harry-potter-hogwarts-mystery-tops-apple-app-store-charts-a-day-after-launch/ |work=[[GamesBeat]] |date=April 26, 2018 |access-date=March 11, 2021 |archive-date=November 9, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201109043244/https://venturebeat.com/2018/04/26/harry-potter-hogwarts-mystery-tops-apple-app-store-charts-a-day-after-launch/ |url-status=live}}</ref> It was the fastest of Jam City's games to reach $100&nbsp;million in revenue,<ref>{{cite news |title=Harry Potter mobile game maker Jam City raises $145 million |last=Takahashi |first=Dean |url=https://venturebeat.com/2019/01/16/harry-potter-mobile-game-maker-jam-city-raises-145-million/ |work=[[GamesBeat]] |date=January 16, 2019 |access-date=March 11, 2021 |archive-date=November 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201108011521/https://venturebeat.com/2019/01/16/harry-potter-mobile-game-maker-jam-city-raises-145-million/ |url-status=live}}</ref> generating {{US$|110&nbsp;million|long=no}} in its first year.<ref>{{cite news |title=Harry Potter: Hogwarts Mystery grosses $110m in first year |last=Taylor |first=Haydn |url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2019-03-14-harry-potter-hogwarts-mystery-grosses-usd110m-in-first-year |work=[[Gamesindustry.biz]] |date=March 14, 2019 |access-date=March 11, 2021 |archive-date=November 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201111205231/https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2019-03-14-harry-potter-hogwarts-mystery-grosses-usd110m-in-first-year |url-status=live}}</ref> By October 2019, it had been downloaded 54.6&nbsp;million times.<ref>{{cite news |title=Harry Potter: Hogwarts Mystery reaches $150m in revenue |last=Dealessandri |first=Marie |url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2019-10-10-harry-potter-hogwarts-mystery-reaches-usd150m-in-revenue |work=[[Gamesindustry.biz]] |date=October 10, 2019 |access-date=March 12, 2021 |archive-date=October 10, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191010131601/https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2019-10-10-harry-potter-hogwarts-mystery-reaches-usd150m-in-revenue |url-status=live}}</ref> The game was nominated for Best Breakthrough Game during the 2019 Google Play Awards.<ref>{{Cite web |date=April 26, 2019 |title=2019 Google Play Awards nominees announced ahead of Google I/O |url=https://www.androidauthority.com/2019-google-play-awards-979976/ |access-date=January 27, 2021 |website=Android Authority |archive-date=March 14, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314185642/https://www.androidauthority.com/2019-google-play-awards-979976/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Kerr |first=Chris |title=Marvel Strike Force and Shadowgun Legends honored at 2019 Google Play Awards |url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/342193/Marvel_Strike_Force_and_Shadowgun_Legends_honored_at_2019_Google_Play_Awards.php |access-date=January 27, 2021 |website=gamasutra.com |archive-date=June 10, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190610072257/https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/342193/Marvel_Strike_Force_and_Shadowgun_Legends_honored_at_2019_Google_Play_Awards.php |url-status=live}}</ref>

Jam City bought the intellectual property, management, and development team of ''Bingo Pop'' from [[Uken Games]] in November 2018, expanding geographically into [[Toronto, Canada]].<ref name="VBBingoPop">{{cite news |last=Takahashi |first=Dean |url=https://venturebeat.com/2018/11/28/jam-city-acquires-bingo-pop-maker-uken/ |title=Jam City acquires Bingo Pop maker from Uken |work=[[VentureBeat]] |date=November 28, 2018 |access-date=February 17, 2021 |archive-date=June 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190629171342/https://venturebeat.com/2018/11/28/jam-city-acquires-bingo-pop-maker-uken/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="TCBingoPop">{{cite news |last=Shieber |first=Jonathan |url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/11/28/jam-city-is-setting-up-a-toronto-shop-by-buying-bingo-pop-from-uken-games/ |title=Jam City is setting up a Toronto shop by buying Bingo Pop from Uken Games |work=[[TechCrunch]] |date=November 28, 2018 |access-date=February 17, 2021 |archive-date=December 27, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181227043929/https://techcrunch.com/2018/11/28/jam-city-is-setting-up-a-toronto-shop-by-buying-bingo-pop-from-uken-games/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="BJBingoPop">{{cite news |last=Amore |first=Samson |url=https://labusinessjournal.com/news/2018/nov/28/jam-city-acquires-bingo-pop-mobile-game/ |title=Jam City Acquires Bingo Pop Mobile Game |work=[[Los Angeles Business Journal]] |date=November 28, 2018 |access-date=February 17, 2021 |archive-date=August 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190805082735/http://labusinessjournal.com/news/2018/nov/28/jam-city-acquires-bingo-pop-mobile-game/ |url-status=live}}</ref> Also in 2018, Jam City and [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]] reached a multi-year deal for Jam City to develop licensed games based on stories and characters from Disney and [[Pixar]].<ref name="Gamesindustry.biz November 2018" /> As part of that deal, Jam City took over the game ''Disney Emoji Blitz''.<ref name="Gamesindustry.biz November 2018" /> Jam City's first new game under its deal with Disney was ''Frozen Adventures'' based on the ''[[Frozen (2013 film)|Frozen]]'' and ''[[Frozen 2]]'' films, which launched the next year.<ref name="Gamesindustry.biz November 2018" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Beresford |first=Trilby |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/jam-city-disney-unveil-first-look-at-frozen-adventures-mobile-game-1234246 |title=Jam City, Disney Unveil First Look at 'Frozen Adventures' Mobile Game |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=August 23, 2019 |access-date=February 18, 2021 |archive-date=December 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201205122418/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/jam-city-disney-unveil-first-look-at-frozen-adventures-mobile-game-1234246 |url-status=live}}</ref>

Jam City announced in January 2019 that it raised {{US$|145&nbsp;million|long=yes}} in funding from [[JPMorgan Chase Bank]], [[Bank of America Merrill Lynch]], and others to support Jam City's acquisitions and global growth initiatives.<ref>{{cite news |last=Takahashi |first=Dean |url=https://venturebeat.com/2019/01/16/harry-potter-mobile-game-maker-jam-city-raises-145-million/ |title=Harry Potter mobile game maker Jam City raises $145 million |work=[[VentureBeat]] |date=January 16, 2019 |access-date=February 17, 2021 |archive-date=November 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201108011521/https://venturebeat.com/2019/01/16/harry-potter-mobile-game-maker-jam-city-raises-145-million/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Shieber |first=Jonathan |url=https://techcrunch.com/2019/01/16/consolidation-is-coming-to-gaming-and-jam-city-raises-145-million-to-capitalize-on-it/ |title=Consolidation is coming to gaming, and Jam City raises $145 million to capitalize on it |work=[[TechCrunch]] |date=January 16, 2019 |access-date=February 17, 2021 |archive-date=November 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201107002029/https://techcrunch.com/2019/01/16/consolidation-is-coming-to-gaming-and-jam-city-raises-145-million-to-capitalize-on-it/ |url-status=live}}</ref> Jam City acquired [[Berlin, Germany|Berlin]]-based studio 231 Play in April.<ref>{{cite news |last=Chapple |first=Craig |url=https://www.pocketgamer.biz/news/70410/jam-city-acquires-berlin-studio-231-play/ |title=Jam City acquires Berlin studio 231 Play |work=[[Pocket Gamer]] |date=April 5, 2019 |access-date=February 18, 2021 |archive-date=December 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201201173926/https://www.pocketgamer.biz/news/70410/jam-city-acquires-berlin-studio-231-play/ |url-status=live}}</ref> DeWolfe told ''[[GamesBeat]]'' that the acquisition of studios in Toronto and Berlin allowed Jam City to expand into more game genres, such as [[Solitaire (game)|solitaire]], [[mahjong]], and [[Bingo (American version)|bingo]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Chris DeWolfe interview: Jam City bets on Disney Frozen 2 collaboration |last=Takahashi |first=Dean |url=https://venturebeat.com/2019/11/14/chris-dewolfe-interview-jam-city-makes-big-bet-on-disney-frozen-2-collaboration/ |work=[[GamesBeat]] |date=November 14, 2019 |access-date=March 10, 2021 |archive-date=October 22, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201022122205/https://venturebeat.com/2019/11/14/chris-dewolfe-interview-jam-city-makes-big-bet-on-disney-frozen-2-collaboration/ |url-status=live}}</ref> According to analytics provider Sensor Tower, solitaire, mahjong, and bingo games ranked among Jam City's top games as of February 2021.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jam City, Inc. |url=https://sensortower.com/android/publisher/jam-city-inc/Jam%2BCity%2C%2BInc. |work=Sensor Tower |access-date=March 10, 2021 |archive-date=April 22, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210422161626/https://sensortower.com/android/publisher/jam-city-inc/Jam%2BCity%2C%2BInc. |url-status=live}}</ref> By mid-2020, Jam City's valuation was estimated at greater than {{US$|2&nbsp;[[1,000,000,000|billion]]|long=no}}.<ref>{{cite news |last=Cherney |first=Max A. |url=https://www.barrons.com/articles/activision-and-ea-could-be-ready-for-a-big-acquisition-51592868351 |title=Mergers Are Heating Up in the Videogame World. EA and Activision Have Lots of Spending Money. |work=[[Barron's (newspaper)|Barron's]] |date=June 22, 2020 |access-date=February 23, 2021 |archive-date=February 11, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210211172143/https://www.barrons.com/articles/activision-and-ea-could-be-ready-for-a-big-acquisition-51592868351 |url-status=live}}</ref>

On May 20, 2021, Jam City announced it would become a [[public company]] through a merger with DPCM Capital Inc., a [[special-purpose acquisition company]]. The merger valued Jam City at {{US$|1.2&nbsp;billion|long=no}}, including debt.<ref name="ReutersSPAC">{{cite news |title=Fenwick, Greenberg Traurig add Jam City's $1.2 bln SPAC deal to mix |last=Jackson |first=Sierra |url=https://www.reuters.com/business/legal/fenwick-greenberg-traurig-add-jam-citys-12-bln-spac-deal-mix-2021-05-20/ |work=[[Reuters]] |date=May 20, 2021 |access-date=May 21, 2021 |archive-date=May 20, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210520202113/https://www.reuters.com/business/legal/fenwick-greenberg-traurig-add-jam-citys-12-bln-spac-deal-mix-2021-05-20/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The merger was expected to close later in 2021.<ref name="ReutersSPAC" /> Through the deal, Jam City was also acquire video game developer [[Ludia]], the maker of games based on the ''[[Jurassic World]]'' franchise, for {{US$|165&nbsp;million|long=no}} in September.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mobile-Game Maker Jam City to Go Public Via SPAC Merger |last=Tse |first=Crystal |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/mobile-game-maker-jam-city-040100384.html |work=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |via=[[Yahoo News]] |date=May 20, 2021 |access-date=May 21, 2021 |archive-date=May 20, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210520104257/https://finance.yahoo.com/news/mobile-game-maker-jam-city-040100384.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Jam City acquires Ludia for $165m|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2021-09-08-jam-city-acquires-ludia-for-usd165m|work=Gamesindustry.biz|date=September 8, 2021}}</ref> In August 2022, Jam City [[Layoff|laid off]] 150–200 people (17% of its headcount), primarily affecting Ludia.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/jam-city-lays-off-17-of-workforce?mc_cid=c0a635d81c&mc_eid=3a2c47bd86 |title=Jam City lays off 17% of workforce |first=Danielle |last=Partis |date=August 5, 2022 |website=[[GamesIndustry.biz]] |access-date=August 5, 2022}}</ref>

== Selected games ==
Most of the games Jam City produces are [[free-to-play]] and use [[microtransaction]]s for players to obtain in-game items or abilities that speed up progression.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-01-09/myspace-s-co-founder-preps-second-act-jam-city-for-possible-ipo |title=MySpace's Co-Founder Preps Second Act Jam City for Possible IPO |date=January 9, 2017 |last=Palmeri |first=Christopher |website=Bloomberg Markets |publisher=Bloomberg LP |access-date=January 10, 2017 |archive-date=January 10, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170110130043/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-01-09/myspace-s-co-founder-preps-second-act-jam-city-for-possible-ipo |url-status=live}}</ref> Jam City's stated business goals include creating high-quality games that generate revenue for years.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxbusiness.com/features/2013/06/14/brain-drain-zynga-loses-top-talent-to-optimistic-rival.html |title=Brain Drain? Zynga Loses Top Talent to Optimistic Rival |date=June 14, 2013 |last=Booton |first=Jennifer |website=Fox Business |access-date=January 23, 2017 |archive-date=February 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170215122645/http://www.foxbusiness.com/features/2013/06/14/brain-drain-zynga-loses-top-talent-to-optimistic-rival.html |url-status=live}}</ref> Jam City's games include both original and licensed [[intellectual property]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Harry Potter: Hogwarts Mystery publisher Jam City will launch SPAC at $1.2B value, buy Ludia for $175M |last=Takahashi |first=Dean |date=May 20, 2021 |access-date=May 20, 2021 |url=https://venturebeat.com/2021/05/20/harry-potter-game-maker-jam-city-will-launch-spac-at-1-2b-value-and-buy-ludia-for-175m/ |work=[[GamesBeat]] |archive-date=May 20, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210520110258/https://venturebeat.com/2021/05/20/harry-potter-game-maker-jam-city-will-launch-spac-at-1-2b-value-and-buy-ludia-for-175m/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In 2017, Jam City had 50&nbsp;million [[monthly active users]] and it had seven games that have ranked in the 100 highest-grossing charts in the [[Apple App Store]].<ref>{{cite news |access-date=June 1, 2018 |url=https://www.fastcompany.com/40446522/jam-city-ceo-chris-dewolfe-talks-mobile-gaming-strategy-and-a-2019-ipo |title=Jam City CEO Chris DeWolfe Talks Mobile Gaming Strategy—And A 2019 IPO |work=Fast Company |location=New York, NY |date=August 9, 2017 |author=Karlin, Susan |archive-date=June 12, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612141220/https://www.fastcompany.com/40446522/jam-city-ceo-chris-dewolfe-talks-mobile-gaming-strategy-and-a-2019-ipo |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |access-date=June 1, 2018 |url=https://venturebeat.com/2018/04/26/harry-potter-hogwarts-mystery-tops-apple-app-store-charts-a-day-after-launch |title=Harry Potter: Hogwarts Mystery tops Apple App Store charts a day after launch |work=VentureBeat |location=San Francisco, CA |date=April 26, 2018 |author=Chan, Stephanie |archive-date=June 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180608215253/https://venturebeat.com/2018/04/26/harry-potter-hogwarts-mystery-tops-apple-app-store-charts-a-day-after-launch/ |url-status=live}}</ref> The company had 31&nbsp;million monthly active users and 1.3&nbsp;billion total game downloads in 2021.<ref name="GamesBeatSPAC" />

