== Products and collaborations ==
Jam City released a monetization tool, AdJolt, in November 2010. It was made available to third-party developers, who would share revenue generated through AdJolt with MindJolt.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://techcrunch.com/2010/11/17/mindjolt-focuses-on-monetization-prepares-to-invade-ipadiphone/ |title=MindJolt Focuses On Monetization, Prepares To Invade iPad/iPhone |date=November 17, 2010 |last=Arrington |first=Michael |website=[[TechCrunch]] |access-date=January 23, 2017 |archive-date=February 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170215203929/https://techcrunch.com/2010/11/17/mindjolt-focuses-on-monetization-prepares-to-invade-ipadiphone/ |url-status=live}}</ref> In December 2012, Jam City launched MasterKey, which enabled the company to develop [[Cross-platform software|cross-platform]] games without creating separate versions for each platform.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://techcrunch.com/2012/12/18/sgn-masterkey-launch/ |title=SGN Makes Its Big Push For Cross-Platform, Mobile-Social Games With The Launch Of Its MasterKey Technology |date=December 18, 2012 |last=Ha |first=Anthony |website=[[TechCrunch]] |access-date=January 23, 2017 |archive-date=September 24, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924044142/https://techcrunch.com/2012/12/18/sgn-masterkey-launch/ |url-status=live}}</ref> MasterKey was described as being technology that "essentially works like a translator or convertor".<ref name="Forbes June2013">{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/lorikozlowski/2013/06/12/the-science-of-social-games/#54899d866c16 |title=The Science of Social Games |date=June 12, 2013 |last=Kozlowski |first=Lori |website=[[Forbes]] |access-date=January 23, 2017 |archive-date=February 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170215125950/http://www.forbes.com/sites/lorikozlowski/2013/06/12/the-science-of-social-games/#54899d866c16 |url-status=live}}</ref>

In December 2014, SGN and Chinese internet technology company [[NetEase]] announced a partnership that enabled ''Cookie Jam'' to be distributed in China beginning in early 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2014/12/15/facebooks-top-game-aims-to-sweeten-up-china.html |title=Facebook's top game aims to sweeten up China |date=December 15, 2014 |last=Levy |first=Ari |website=CNBC |publisher=CNBC LLC |access-date=January 20, 2017 |archive-date=June 8, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170608090851/http://www.cnbc.com/2014/12/15/facebooks-top-game-aims-to-sweeten-up-china.html |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.builtinla.com/2014/12/16/sgn-launches-cookie-jam-china-it-was-not-easy |title=SGN launches Cookie Jam into China: it was not easy |date=December 16, 2014 |last=Reim |first=Garrett |website=Built in LA |access-date=January 19, 2017 |archive-date=February 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170215120140/http://www.builtinla.com/2014/12/16/sgn-launches-cookie-jam-china-it-was-not-easy |url-status=live}}</ref>

